<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-921-942  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 921 942.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Iandamp;CS (Instrumentation andamp; Control Systems)  Sept 1989 v62 n9p103(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Custom ball valves solve tire curing problem, save money.andO;(Worcester Controls Corp valves in tire plant)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Miles, Michael E.; Labs, Wayne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Worcester Controls Corp (Marlborough, MA) installed its SeriesMP44 stainless steel ball valve (with Series 39 pneumaticactuator) in the tire press and curing system of a midwestern tireplant.andP;  The plant manufactures tractor and heavy equipment tires,but the brass-bodied globe values were breaking down under thehigh temperature, fast rising and high steam pressures, and longexposure to multiple cycles of hot steam and cold water.andP;  The MP44valve and Series 39 actuator had been tested through at least150,000 cycles at another tire plant and was found to solve thedegradation problems at the plant in question.andP;  Advantages includehigh resistance to corrosion, simple and rapid replacement, andreduced system downtime and maintenance costs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Worcester Controls Corp. (products).andO;Topic:     Control EquipmentApplicationsCase StudyManufacturing.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartphotograph.andO;Caption:   Architectural diagram of the MP44 ball valve. (chart)Brass-bodied globe values traditionally used in rubber molding.andO;(chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>